CONCLUSION

After an extensive application of a classical logistic model, which we strengthened with quadratic effects and cross-tabulations, we were faced with a major problem in the context of linear regression: multicollinearity. Therefore, penalized regression models were a solution to overcome this problem, by selecting (or not) variables on our whole dataset. Four models have been developed, namely the Ridge, the Lasso, the Adaptive Lasso and the Elastic Net. These penalized regressions have the main advantage of simplicity of interpretation of the results but also of implementation of the algorithms.

We then introduced classification tree models, starting with the CART algorithm, which is simple to implement and interpret. Nevertheless, a tree built under this algorithm is subject to a high risk of overfitting. It is to this extent that tree pruning methods allow to reinforce the results, by proposing a less complex tree but just as rich in generalization power.

Aggregation methods are a method for building strong learners by mobilizing weak learners. To this extent, the first algorithms we presented were Bagging and Random Forest, parallel aggregation methods for enhancing predictive quality by bootstrapping examples into a set consisting of the most complex tree. The generalization power obtained by our model increases with the number of bootstrapped samples within our sample. We are therefore faced with a dilemma between performance and computer time.

And then the Boosting, a sequential aggregation method where the reinforcement of the learning is established by assigning higher weights to the misclassified individuals during the previous iteration. In this respect, two main algorithms were presented, namely Adaboost and Gradient Boosting. Their main advantage over Random Forest is the computation time, even if more hyperparameters have to be determined.

According to our results, the Boosting methods provide better results in terms of accuracy. To go further than our two basic algorithms, we have also presented results from XGBoost, an algorithm that enhances the performance of Gradient Boosting, and SAMME.R, an algorithm that enhances the performance of Adaboost.
